emography, the world history of famines, and the story of American immigration, the Great Irish Famine is presented here from a variety of new perspectives. Moving away from the traditional narrative historical approach to the catastrophe, Ó Gráda concentrates instead on fresh insights available through interdisciplinary and comparative methods. He highlights several economic and sociological features of the famine previously neglected in the literature, such as the part played by traders and markets, by medical science, and by migration. Other topics include how the Irish climate, usually hospitable to the potato, exacerbated the failure of the crops in 1845-1847, and the controversial issue of Britain's failure to provide adequate relief to the dying Irish. Ó Gráda also examines the impact on urban Dublin of what was mainly a rural disaster and offers a critical analysis of the famine as represented in folk memory and tradition. The broad scope of this book is matched by its remarkable range of sources, published and archival. The book will be the starting point for all future research into the Irish famine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aBallina (Mayo).  aBoard of Works.  aCatholic clergy.  aConnacht.  aCork City.  aDonegal.  aDublin.  aGalway.  aKennedy, Liam.  aKerry.  aLeinster.  aLimerick.  aMayo.  aMokyr, Joel.  aMunster.  aNorth Dublin Union.  aO'Connell, Daniel.  aRoscommon.  aSligo.  aTipperary.  aTyrone.  aWaterford.  aWicklow.  aact of union 1800.  aagency.  abeggars.  acholera.  acorruption.  adiet.  aemigration.  aevictions.  afamine fever.  afolk memory.  aideology.  aimpact of famine.  amedical practitioners.  apoor law.  apotato blight.  apublic works.  aspeculation.  aturnips.  a